const faqs = [{"question": "Does Elysium Basis increase testosterone?", "answer": "No, Elysium Basis is not designed to increase testosterone. It is a NAD+ precursor supplement containing Nicotinamide Riboside (NR) and Pterostilbene, aimed at supporting cellular health and healthy aging. While NAD+ plays a role in many biological processes, there is no clinical evidence that Basis supplementation directly increases testosterone levels."}, {"question": "Is Elysium Basis legitimate or a scam?", "answer": "Elysium Health is a legitimate company with genuine scientific credentials. Co-founded by MIT biologist Leonard Guarente, the company has a credible scientific advisory board. Their core ingredient, Nicotinamide Riboside, has real research behind it showing it can raise NAD+ levels in humans. However, the leap from 'raises NAD+' to 'slows aging' remains unproven in human clinical trials."}, {"question": "What are the side effects of Elysium Basis?", "answer": "Elysium Basis is generally well-tolerated. Nicotinamide Riboside has been shown to be safe in multiple human trials at the doses used. Some users report mild gastrointestinal discomfort, flushing, or headaches, particularly when starting. As with any supplement, individuals on medications should consult their physician before use."}, {"question": "How does NAD+ relate to hormone health?", "answer": "NAD+ is a coenzyme involved in hundreds of metabolic processes, including those that support mitochondrial function, DNA repair, and cellular energy production. While these processes indirectly support overall health (including the endocrine system), NAD+ supplementation has not been shown to directly improve testosterone levels or correct hormonal deficiencies. Hormone optimization requires targeted treatment."}, {"question": "Is Elysium Basis worth the price?", "answer": "At $40 to $60 per month, Elysium Basis is priced at a premium compared to standalone NR supplements. The premium reflects the brand, the proprietary formulation (Basis combines NR with pterostilbene), and the scientific advisory team. Whether it is worth it depends on your goals: if you are looking for general cellular health support and can afford it, it is a credible option. If you are looking to address low testosterone or hormone-related symptoms, it is not the right product."}, {"question": "Can I take Elysium Basis with TRT?", "answer": "NAD+ precursors like NR are generally considered safe to take alongside TRT, but you should always discuss supplement additions with your prescribing physician. At Strong Health, we evaluate your complete health picture and can advise whether NAD+ supplementation might complement your treatment plan."}];

